Unbridled central bank governors?
PRAGUE – Lately, there has been widespread criticism of central banks in advanced economies.
The main complaints go something like this: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their powers have expanded too rapidly, and they are endangering the economy.
This critique – which strangely enough resonates among ideological camps that should be at loggerheads, such as liberals and neo-Marxists – is entirely misplaced.
Critics fail to understand that modern central banks must not only contain inflation but also maintain long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature, fluctuating within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
In fighting deflation caused by weak demand and containing high inflation driven by strong demand, central banks must be equally “active.”
While the battle is entirely symmetrical, public perception is oddly lopsided, especially in countries where people are financially conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. Czech savers save very little, and the loan-deposit ratio is still well below 100%.
The Czechs worry about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached a 13-year low last year, and the National Bank of the Czech Republic, which I have served as deputy governor since 2013, has been working to eliminate deflationary risks.
Other complaints about the policies of developed country central banks since 2008 are that these policies create redistribution effects.
Of course they do, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while lowering them benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong currency; exporters prefer a weak one.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; it is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also claim that central banks have failed to meet their inflation targets, so their activism was not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even combine these contradictory criticisms in the same sentence, as if blaming someone for causing casualties while firing blanks.
The reality is that global central banks succeeded – and spectacularly so – in maintaining price stability and purchasing power after the global financial crisis.
If not for their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, a massive plunge in asset prices, and the complete collapse of both financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to dealing with the crisis (what role central banks played in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another question).
In a system using non-asset-backed elastic currency, for purchasing power to remain roughly constant over time, the money supply must change.
Therefore, price stability, not the quantity of money, is the key issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems many economies faced after 2008.
In this context, the central bank took necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
There is no "activism" here; only an eternal mission that needs to be achieved.
If you find this argument arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If their money's purchasing power has been severely damaged since 2008, they will naturally seek to exchange it for other currencies, precious metals, or other savings methods.
This is rare in the developed world.
Naturally, many central banks fail to meet their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal "temperature" of the economy as annual inflation around 2%.
) This is unwelcome, but it does not lead to disaster, particularly considering that some price declines stem from supply – rather than demand – shocks, such as plummeting oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net importers of oil.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this by increasing sales by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
Probably not.
After all, private companies' planned profits and revenues often deviate by 10% or more from actual results.
Most firms face fewer variables in their operating environments than central banks do.
Given that, how can you expect the central bank to always hit precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I am not saying the central bank should not work hard to get close to its targets.
They certainly should.
In addition, they should absolutely not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
But, when evaluating central banks, one needs to strike an appropriate balance.
They indeed need to stop saying things that are not true – for example, that their policy toolkit is not only nearly exhausted but has already approached exhaustion.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and an unlimited supply of ammunition at their disposal.
These weapons come in different calibers and have varying degrees of effectiveness at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economies under all circumstances.
But the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
The central bank governor should tell ignorant critics to stop.
Our critics cannot clearly and credibly explain why price stability is a wrong goal, what key objectives the central bank should pursue; nor can they explain what fundamentally different approach they should have taken since 2008.
The reason for this is simple: the policy adopted by developed country central banks since the crisis was correct.
In fact, it pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
